{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_frenchbulldog_ver04/data/sn83045433/00280764139/1920121401/0642.xml":{"full_text":"A\nCOMMERCIAI\nFINANCIAL\nSECTION TWO.\nHEAVY SELLING\nMAKES RECORD\nFOR NEW YORK\nRange of Issues Traded\nSets New Mark for Single\nDay in Market.\nQUEER TALES ABOUT\n\nSome of Staunchest Stocks\nDisplay Unexpected\nWeaknesses.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 13 HtM.tr gen ral\nselling again featured the stock\nmarket today. Transactions exceeded\n1,400.000 shares, and the range\n?f Issues traded in probably surpasses\nany previous record for a\nsingle day. Losses were again the\nrule, with weakness breaking out\nIn some of the staunchest stocks;\nuch, for instance, as Royal Dutch.\nBears Roebuck. Southern Pacific.\nBaldwin and Steel. At times the\nmarket was very thin and along\nin the late trading it developed\nsymptoms of disorderly- liquidation.\n,To those who looked ?for influences\nin the morning news or the\ndevelopments over the week-end, the\ndecline came as more or less of a\nsurprise. The showing of the twelve\nFederal Reserve banks was much\nbetter than anticipated, with thereserve\nratio 44.5 per cent, which was\nthe highest since June 18. Moreover,\nthe reports of the favorable\nprogress made in the organising of\nthe $100,000,000 corporation under\nthe Edge act gave promise of some\nof the most helpful and constructive\nwork undertaken since the armistice.\nIn addition to this there\nwas general expectation of an easier\nmoney situation after the middle\nof the month.\nM*b Feeling Rife.\nUnder such circumstances, it\nwould seem futile to go into a discussion\nof values or other factors\nordinarily regarded as fundamenthis.\nThe market at present furnishes\nmore of a study in mob psychology\nthan anything else. I^ack\nof confidence, fears of unfavorable\ndevelopments of a mysterious and\nunknown character, rumors that\ncannot be confirmed, all play their\np part in current operations. In addition\nto these is the Inexorable\nmargin call, and the forced selling\nby impecunious holders.\nAll sorts of stories a to in circulation\nabout fortunes swept away\nand of the poverty that has suddenly\ncome upon those whose\nnames for years have been symbols\nof affluence.\nBis Rmik Fix per ted.\nAipong the experienced habitues\npf the Street\" the feeling is general\nthat \"the worst is yet to come.\"\nThe decline thus far has been too\norderly, they say, and one final,\nsmashing wide open break must give\nthe signal that the last agony of\nliquidation has been undergone.\nThese, however. ar? merely the\nviews of professionals, who. while\nveterans in service, have little to\nshow for the years they have spent\nIn following the shifting changes of\nthe tape.\nIt would be rather futile under\nthese conditions to indulge in solemn\nanalysis of underlying forces.\nThe selling fever probably will have\nto run fts course before any consideration\nis given to value and\nthe progress now being made along\nconstructive lines.\nSterling was firm around 3.44%.\nGrain was higher. Cotton broke\nsharply under the influence of the\ngovernment estimate, showing over\n12.?0t).000 bales. Call money ruled\n?t 7 per cent.\nCommercial Bureau\nOpens in Shanghai\nAn office of the Bureau of Foreign\nand Domestic Commerce was opened\nat Shanghai on December 11 by\nCommercial Attache Julean Arnold, j\naccording to a cablegram received by\nthe Department In Washington yesterday.\nThe office Is located in the\nChinese-American Bank Building\nand will be In charge of Mr. Arnold\nuntil funds are available for the apyclnimcrt\nof an assistant conm?rcial\nattache. The office was opened\nin response to requests from the\nAmerican Chamber of Commerce at\nShanghai and from a number of\nChambers of Commerce In the United\nStates.\nIt is hoped by the Department of\nCommerce that through the Shanghai\noffice a service will be rendered\nto American business men making\nan opening in China which will approximate\nthe service now'rendered\nIn the United States through district\nand co-operative offices of the Department.\nCotton'8 Future\nRests on Business\nIn their cotton letter. Issued at\nthe close of yesterday's session,\nThomson and McKinnon said in\npart:\n'We have had today the government\nestimate on the size of the\ncrop. This Is usually the event of\nthe cotton season. The estimate oI\n12.987.000 bales was somewhat in\nexcess of the average private estimates,\nbut did not show such important\nvariation as to cause violent\nfluctuations, especially as the report\nwas to some extent disconnted by\nthe sagging market thlch we have\nexperienced the last few days, followed\nby a fair decline today prior\nto the publication of report. Ther*\nis nothing in the figures to necessitate\na change of opinion, since\nthe future of the market re*ts on\n^he development in business.\nV. S. Shipping Board\nDisposes of Vessel\nThe United States Shipping Board\nyesterday announced the sale for\n11.739.000 of the steel cargo boat Hy\nS. drove to the Atlantic, Gulf and\nPacific Steamship Company, of Baltimore.\nThis boat will be operated\nbetween Atlantic and PaclAc ports,\nthrough the canal.\nI v'\nSports\n|f] $1je j\nWASHDJi\nU. S. LABOR CONDITIONS T\nUNDERGO GREAT CHANGES\n______________________\nDays of Falling Prices and Business Depression\nMainly Responsible.\nIn these days of falling prices and business depression one can\nscarcely pick up a newspaper without seeing items about closing\nfactories or reduced operating time. It has been predicted that this\nwinter will see thousands of idle workers. Reports indicate that\nwhereas a few months ago there was a great scarcity of labor, there\nis now a surplus in many industries. It has been said that these\nconditions are resulting in much greater efficiency in the workmen\nwho are in fear of losing their jobs; also in a willingness to acctpt\nlower wages.\nIf commodity prices continue to decline wages will also have\nto take the same course sooner or later. Those who have the best\ninterests of the country at heart hope that the fall in prices will\nprecede any fall in wages. So far that has been (he case. There are\nmany instances where manufacturers have made heavy cuts in the\nprices of their products, but at the same time announcing that there\nwould be no reduction in wages. In many instances where wages\nhave been reduced it has been done at the request of the employes\nwho preferred to take less pay rather than have the factory close.\nIf there could be some stabilization of prices and if the long expected\nrevival of business should materialize, it might be possible\nto prevent any furtAer drop in wages for the present. So far neithei\nof these conditions have been brought about.\nSome idea of the decrease in the volume of employment can be\nobtained from the monthly reports of the U. S. Bureau of Laboi\nStatistics on employment in selected industry. The bureau tabulate:\neach month the reports from 600 to 700 establishments in 13 differenl\nmanufacturing industries and in c?el mining. The 13 industries ar<\niron and steel, automobiles, car building and repairing, cotton manufacturing,\ncotton finishing, hosiery and underwear, woolen, silk, men's\nclothing, leather manufacturing, boots and shoes, paper making am\ncigars.\nThe reports are tabulated to show each month for identical es\ntablishments the number of employes on the payroll this year ant\nlast year and the total amount of the payroll in each period. Ir\norder to get a rough summary of the general course of employment il\nis possible to add together the total number of 'employes on the pay]\nroll of these 13 industries for each month and then obtain the relatior\ni of the number this year to the number employed at the same tim?\nlast year. Strictly speaking such a comparison between successive\nI months is not justified, for although the number and identity of the\nj establishments reporting this year and last for any month are th(\nj same the sdme firms are not always included in successive months\nThe fact that the total number of establishments reporting is fairly\nconstant renders this objection less serious.\nIn the following tabulation we have omitted coal mining because\nit is not reported for all months. Also the iron and steel industry\nI has been omitted because the strike in the latter part of 1919 renders\nany comparison there invalid for our purposes. The following tabic\nshows the total monthly volume of employment in 12 selected in!\ndustries from March to October of this year compared with the rej\nspective months of last year.\n[MONTHLY COMPARISON OF EMPLOYMENT IN TWELVE\nINDUSTRIES.\nNumberof\nEstablishments Per Cent\nReporting Number on Payroll Increase\nMonth Both Yearsl 1919 1920 or Decrease\nMarch 582 410,629 501,845 +22.2\nApril 551 419.671 499.686 +19.1\nI May 568 405.879 463.636 4-14-2\nJune 553 434.749 476,348 -f 9-6\n(July 541 436,662 433.015 0.8\nAugust 536 402,604 374,702 6.9\nSeptember 562 485,847 450,269 7.3\nOctober 577 5<9^H 445-394 >4 3\nAmount of Payroll\n1919 1920\nMarch 582 $10,628,930 $15,887,531 +49 5\nApril 551 10,603.407 15443.378 +45.6\nMay 568 10,487,945 15.t5t.307 +44-5\nIJune 553 11,508,151 15.768,740 +370\nJuly 54' 11.259,523 13.770.747 +22-3\nAugust 536 10,393,617 12,322,686 +18.6\nSeptember 562 13.433.869 15,100,974 +124\nOctober 577 14,853,012 15,057,160 1.4\nIn March, 1920, the 582 establishments reported the total numbri\nof employes as 501,845 compared with 410,629 in March, 1919. Thi'\nis an increase of 22.2 per cent compared with the previous year. Ir\nApril this year the number of employes reported by 551 firms wa:\n19.1 per cent greater than the year before. In May the percentagi\nincrease had fallen to 14.2 and in June to 9.6. In July the numbei\nof employes reported by 541 establishments was 0.8 per cent less\nthan in July, 1919. In August and September the number of employe:\nwas approximately 7 per cent less than the year before and in Octo\nber the number was 14.3 per cent less.\nThese figures show a steady decrease in the number of employe:\non the payroll compared to the corresponding periods of last year. I\nthese figures m^y be assumed to represent conditions in the countr;\nas a whole there are about 15 per cent less persons employed it\nmanufacturing csViblishments now than a year ago, while 8 month:\nago there were 22 per cent more employes than at the corresponding\nperiod of 1919.\nIn March, 1920, the total amount of the payroll of the 582 firm:\nreporting was nearly 50 per cent greater than the year before. Ir\nspite of the fact that the reports for April and May showed a market\ndecrease in the\" relative number of employes the total payroll main\ntained about the same relation to 1919 as in March. This indicate:\nthat average wages were increasing^ Since March the relation of th<\n1920 payroll to that of 1919 has decreased in about the same proportion\nas the number of employes decreased. In the last two months\nthe decrease in the payroll has been even more rapid, indicating\nslight decrease in average wages.\nCopyright, 1929. Washington Herald.)\nRAILWAY HEADS\" LIVING SOARS IN\nAIR THEIR VIEWS CONSTANTINOPLl\nI. C. C. Hears Protests Arising Enormous Rise in Costs Make;\nFrom Recent Ruling on \"Living\" Impossible?\"LinIntrastate\nRates. ger in Misery.\"\nView, of the State railway com- Co8t ot livin* ln Constantinopl.\nmissions on the action of the Inter- has risen approximately 2.00# pe\nstate Commerce Commission sane- cent since the beK'nninK ot the war\ntioning an increase in intrastate according to advices to the Depart\nrates to the level of interstate rates, ment of Commerce yesterday fron\nto maintain the uniformity of the Consul Charles E. Allen. At thi\nState and interstate railroad rates. same time the UvlnR coit has rlse?\nwere heard by the commission yes- 115 ptr cent ln the Unlted State'\nterday. State rate control organi- and 353 Per cent\nsations represented at the hearing At th* time 0f the\nwere from Utah. Florida. Illinois. lncrease 1300 per cent-\nMichigan. Indiana, Ohio, and other th4t time- *P,U 0f the re\nState, where the question of Juris- ^\".nd^A^cV ^'in^'of^e'\ndiction $ver State rates as yet has dining, living: costs have increased\nnot been brought to an Issue. Rents have increased 400 per cen\nFrim the tenor of the arguments 'or dweUlners ana 900 per cent foi\nbusiness buildings. In practice thi\nof spokesmen for the State railway proportion easily reached 2,000 pel\ncommissions, as opposed to the ac- cent.\nquisition of control by the Inter- Concerning the rise In price*. Con\nstate Commerce Commission over gul Allen says:\nState regardless of the \"We are curious to know how th<\nwishes or State organisations. It is population of Constantinople livei\nn0t4eipected., the hearln? held under such conditions. Foreigner!\nyesterday will serve to bring the admire Its endurance, without be\ntwo factions to an understanding, jng able to explain the cause. But\nIn the case of each State, where the the solution of this problem is ven\nInterstate Commerce Commission simple. It is that the people ol\nhas ordered an increase in intra- Constantinople no longer live, but\nstate rates In conformity to the high linger in misery. And the peoplt\nlevel of tatefstate rates, it is ex- able to feed themselves properly\npected that court proceedings will hardly number 20 per cent of th<\nI be brought to contest the authority total population.\"\nof the Interstate Commerce Commission.\nThe hearing, were arranged by state to Hi. increased intrastat\nthe Interstate Commerce Commi,- tariffs. Similar hearing, will b\n'or ?th? Purpose of giving an held by the commi,,ion later to hea\n7\" 1' ,to th- the argument, of the State organ*\n.1 eipre,, their view, xations of the remaining slate;\nbefore the commission Issue, a for- where the question of Jurlsdictloi\nmal order to the railroad, of each of State rate, I, pending.\nWill Be Found on\npip?\nGTON. D. C? TUES1\nimonoN CROP\nSHOWS MILD GAIN\nOVER LAST YEAR\nTotal Increase of Million\nBales Indicated in\nReport.\nAVERAGE 506.9 LBS.\nTexas Leads in Production\nWith Comfortable Margin.\nSouth Carolina Next.\nk The cotton crop of 1*20-21 totaled\n12.9S7.000 bales, the Department of\nAgriculture announced yesterday.\nThis does not include linters. The\ntotal production in 1919 was 11.420,\n673 bales.\nThe average weight per running\nbale was estimated at 506.9 pounds,\ngross, compared with 504.2 pounds in\n1919.\n1 The price per pound of lint cott\nton to producers December 1, 1920,\nwas 14 cents, compared with a De.\ncember 1 price of 35.6 cents a year\nago.\nThe estimated production for 1920.\nwith comparison, b States follows:\n1920 1919\nVirginia 19.000 22.523\nI North Carolina. 840,000 830.293\nI South Carolina.. 1.530.000 1.426.146\nI Georgia 1,400,000 1,659.529\nFlorida..... 18.000 15.923\nAlabama....... 660.000 713.236\nMississippi 885.000 960.886\nLouisiana 380,000 297.681!\n!Texas 4.200.000 3,098.967\nArkansas 1,160.000 884,473\nTennessee 310.000 310.044\n1 Missouri 85,000 64.031\nOklahoma 1.300,000 1.016.929\nCalifornia 150.000 5O07\n'Arizona 110.000 59.849\nAll others 15.000 4.947 i\nWHEATRALUES,\nCLOSING HIGHER\nFutures Are fought Heavily\nAgainst Export in Chicago\nMarket.\nCHICAGO, Dec. 13.?Buying of\nwheat futures against export sales,\ncovering by shorts, combined with\nlight offers after an early rush to\nsell, caused a stronger tone in\nwheat, and prices at the close were\nI at material gains here today, the\nfinish being 2U to 3 cents higher\nEarly selling was due to the slump\nin stocks and pessimistic financial\nrepons, but the offerings were soon\ncleanpd up by commission houses\nand local traders who were on the\nbuying side of the market most\nof the day.\nOther grains also closed strong,\nbad weather affecting corn, while\nthere was little pressure. Corn\nclosed 1 to 2Uc higher, oats rs to\nSc up, rye was ?4c lower to 2 cents\n1 higher, while barley was l\\4c lower\n5 to I cent higher.\nIn corn, lowest prices for the day\nr were made at the start, after which\nj there was an irregularly higher\n5 trend. Cash interests were credited\nwith buying December. which\ngained about 1 cent on the other\ndeliveries. Local shorts were fair\n5 buyers.\nf Moderate gains were scored in the\nr oats market, but trade was without\nfeature, operations being mostly by\nlocals. The strength in other grains\n5 was a factor and there was no spe5\ncial selling pressure.\nThe cash trade in provisions is\n5 stagnant in spite of reduced prices,\ni As a result there was little demand\n1 for futures and the market was\nlower. Pork declined 47 cents, lard\n15 to 37 cents and ribs 32 to 35 cents.\n\nWheat's Statistical\nPosition Is. Strong\nThe daily wheat letter of Thomson\nand McKinnon. grain brokers\nissued at the close of yesterday's\nmarket, read as follows: \"Export\ndemand for wheat has again been\nin evidence. Volume of business Is\nI restricted by a scarcity of offerings.\nI The visible supply of wheat in deI\ntail makes a rather startling showing.\nNot only is the total visible\nabout one-half of that of a year\na ago. but. of the total Y>f 48,700,000.\n33.000.000 is at the seaboard, or\nnearby, therefore not available for\ndomestic milling purposes when the\ndemand revives. Argentine markets\nwere lower under favorable weather\n,/or hardest. On the othsr hand, exs\ncesgive rains are reported in New\nSouth Wales and drought in India.\nIn the face .of a demoralized stock\nmarket, and with investors in wheat\ndecidedly timid, the sharp upturn\nj in the early market is noteworthy.\nTo us it is significant of a com8\nplete liquidation of unnecessary\nl holdings in grains. The system of\ni trading for future deliveries in the\ngrain markets permits complete\nliquidation. There is no such\nmethod in commodities and indus1\ntries. The statistical position is\nstrong. It ought not to be necessary\nto refer to this. The sharp advance\nin prices, despite gloom over the\nbusiness world generally, ought to\nbe sufficient indication of the cont\ndition of the market,\nr\nr Corn Appears to Be\nWell Liquidated\ns In their dally corn letter, issued\ns at the close of yesterday's market,\nThomson and llcKinnon. (rain bro.\nkera. aaid in part: \"Thla market.\nt like wheat, gives every indication\nr of being well liquidated. The un[\ndertone today haa been quite firm.\nt although no particular (levelop,\nmenta. On the queatlon of deflar\ntion we want to aay the price of\ncorn on the farms haa determined\nfrom the commercial price, and taking\nInto consideration the advance\nIn freight rates and other expenses\nIs somewhat lower than In 1915,\nwhile at the same time the number\nB of farm animals, exclusive of\nr horses and mules, is greater than In\n1913. With the restoration of con?\nfldence In business circles, devrlopi\nments as they attpear should favor\nUi? bolder of ootb.\n'V\nPage 3 of This 1\ngto3\nDAY. DECEMBER 1'\n\nI MEN AND\nBy R1CHARI\nA lie travels on a thousand\nGrinds, the truth on one.\nThere are many li<s being told\ntoday, and not a few fn Philadelphia.\nReports as to the insolvency of this\nor that concern, the prospective\nfailure of such and such a Arm. are\nwhispered by trouseted gossips and\nspread by others of that ilk.\nIn New York they have a law making\nIt a criminal offense to give currency\nto an untruth that affects the\ncredit of a corporation. Pennsylvania\nmay have no such specific law.\nbut under the common law there is\nlittle doubt there is adequate basis\nfor action.\nTbo substantial houses of this\ncity are well and honestly managed.\nThey have ample reserves for emergencies.\nBut idle and malicious gossips\ncan do them and the city much\ninjury.\nEarnest. conscientious citizens\nshould take measures to stop the\nlo6se-tongued liars. Demand from\nthe babblers authority for or proof\nof what they say. Tell them you are\ngoing to report at once to the persons\nmost concerned. Don't have\nany quaims. A spreader of commercial\nuntruth is little short of a public\nenemy and never more so than\nj in times like these. Idle or malicious\nwords of one person may undermine\nconfidence in houses with\nrecords of twenty-five, fifty or seventy-five\nyears of commercial honesty.\nservice and general worth.\nOut with the liars.\nIf you want to know the standing\nof any concern, get it from your/\nbanker. It is his business to know\nor assist you in ascertaining such\ninformation if it is essential to you.\nMeanwhile, get the branding iron\nready for use on the trousered gossip.\nHe is ubiquitous and ever busy.\nAnd always remember that a lie\nINCREASED SHOE\nSALES IN BOSTON\nMarket Is Slightly Strengthened?Demand\nfor Women's\nFootwear Increases.\nSpecial to Business Section of Tbo Washington\nHerald.)\nBOSTON. Dec. 13. Approaching\nChristmas buying has given a little\nstability to retail prices on shoes.\nFurther concessions are not expected\nby the public until January. This\nhas strengthened the market slightly.\nRetailers are reporting an increase\nin sales of from 8 to 20 per\ncent over the previous week, but\nthis does not include the men's shoe\ndepartments, which remain rather\ninytive. The demand is for fancy\nfootwear for women.\nUnemployment in all industries\nhas increased 48 per cent in Massachusetts\nsince last October, and the\nshoe industry has contributed Its\nfull share toward this condition,\nand it is now concerning itself with\na readjustment of wages. In the\nnature of things the merchants will\nbe in the market soon to order\nshoes, and they expect even lower\nprices than they are paying today\non small orders, but the manufacturers\nhave no reliable basis on\nwhich to figure prices for future\ndeliveries until they have struck a\ndependable basis of wages.\nOne of the large factories in Boston\nis expected to lay off a large\npercentage of its help within a few\ndays. Brockton is trying to settle\nthe Question through agreement\nwith the unions of' shoe workers.\nWhile one group of unions in Brockton\nhas withdrawn a request for\nan increase in wages, another group\nof unions, having departments in\nall the factories, has filed a demand\nfor an increase ranging between\n17 and 25 per cent. But the Manufacturers'\nAssociation takes the\nstand that this is no time for wage\nI increase, and that there should be\nJ a reduction instead.\nIn Lynn the shoe manufacturers\n.have asked the operatives to accept\na reduction in the bonus which has\nbeen paid to them for more than a\nyear. This issue remains unsettled,\nbut the unions are insistent that\nthey will not accept it. although\nthey are informed that the alternative\nwill be a closing of the factories.\nA SAVING\nYou could not fir\nconvenient investn*\nAccount in this bank\nYou can add to it\nthe interest is compo\na year and no matte\nchange in value, you\nworth one hundred\nMake our Savinj\ninvestment headquar\npmd on Ch?ckimg mm\nUnionTru:\nOF THE DISTKI\nI EDWARD J.STEL]\n,i\nSection\nflefalfl\n1. 1920.\nBUSINESS\nSPILLANL J\ni travels on a thousand winds, the\ntruth on one.\n80 it's 1.000 to 1 any tale of impending\nfailure# you hear Is false.\nBoston may be drooping a bit\nfinancially, commercially and industrially.\nbut intellectually it stands j\nsupreme. No Bostonian feels that j\nhe or she is really dressed up wtth|\nout eye-glasses. Now a Boston\nspaniel goes forth dally with tor- j\nI toise shell goggles athwart its aris j\ntocratic nose. The dog is Nemo,\nowned by Mr. and Mrs. C. W. Allen.\nThey say Nemo's eyes have\nbeen affected by the sharp east\nwind while automobiling. but the 1\nfact probably Is he, like other den-\nisens of the Back Bay, has over-\nstrained his optio nerves by study.\nOne of the Chicago mall order\nI houses reports Its November, 1920,\nbusiness 22.69 per cent below that of\nNovember, 1919. Mall order .business\nis likely to be poor for many\nI months. The bulk of mail order purchases\ncomes from rural communities\nand small towns. The great decline\nin the price of wheat, corn,\ncotton, wool and other farm products\nhas reduced the buying power\nj of the agriculturist to a decided de-\ngree. That is one of the things that j\nwill affect the whole merchandising\nI system of the country adversely for j\nnot a few months.\nEvidence of improvement is likely\nj to be manifested in the automobile\ntire business soon. Today the consumption\nof tires is greater than the\nproduction. This means, of course,\nthat stocks are decreasing. What Is\ntrue of the tire busines applies also\nto automobiles. A turn for the better\nin that line should come early\njin the new year. Those best informed\nin the automotive Industry;\ndo not look fqr anything more than\na moderate demand In 1921. Whatever\nincrease there is. they believe,\nwill be in trucks and tractors rather\nj than in passenger cars.\n1 Copyright. 1M0. Faklic I*4f.r C?.)\nPARTNERSHIP IN\nINDUSTRY URGED\nHenry A. Wise Wood Tells\nCredit Men U.S. Trade Abroad\nShould Be Protected.\nPHILADELPHIA, P?? Dec. 13.?\nThat the banking and the industrial\nj interests of the United States should.\nunite and create a machinery for\ndoing business with foreign markets\ndespite the present rate of exchange;\nthat a governmental policy of pro-!\ntection should be inaugurated\nwhereby our citizens and their busi-'\nness shall be protected in foreign\nlands, and that our merchant marine\nshould be expanded until it carrics\nthe commerce of the world, were\ningredients of the recipe for American\nprosperity suggested by Henry\nA. Wise Wood. New York printing\nmachinery manufacturer, speaking\nat the luncheon of the Philadelphia\nCredit Men's Association at the\nAdelphia Hotel yesterday. Mr. Wood\nalso spoke strongly against the\npresent league of nations, urging the\nre-establishment and strengthening\nthe The Hague tribunal.\n\"The open shop.\" said Mr. Wood,\n\"now being talked of so strongly,\nis the reassertion of Americanism.\nIt merely means-the right to work\nwhere we will and employ whom we\nwill. There is no crown for either\nlabor or capital, tire one that tries\nto rule is doomed to defeat.\n\"We have changed from a debtor\nto a credXor nation and it will inevitably\ndrag us into international\naffairs. We must find world markets\nto get interest on our money.\nWe need cleverness, ingenuity and\ngood business judgment Iik organization\nto take over the commercial\nand industrial power of the world.\n\"We must become the maritime\npower of the world. To do business\nwith the world we must have\nour merchant fleets under our own'\nflag and protected by a bigger navy, j\n\"We must become a great bank-j\ning nation. To do this our banks\nand our industries must form a\npartnership. When the salesman of\nAmerican products poes abroad he\nshould be accompanied by the Amer-1\nlean credit salesman. Our banks\nand industries should get together\nand plan campaigns. Now is the\ntime to loosen up and extend credits.\nThe way to make this &untry a\nbanking nation is by the use of tl?e\nHdge law.\"\nC^oi-rte r\n15 lb and H Si?.\nNoriKwest\n\n5\nACCOUNT\nid t more reliable or\nsnt than a Savings\nat any time you wish,\nunded regularly twice\nr how other securities\nir deposits are always\n:ents on the dollar,\n[s Department your\nters.\n3% M 5wia|? Accoanti\nst Company\nCT Or COLUMBIA\nIAVAGEN, President J\ni f\nr QUALJT\nI REALTY\nf i\n\n\nP?b New Meaberehip\nCupiip Over tkc Tap\nMfej\nIHh^ jB\nVICTOR B. DEYBER,\nVice president'of the Second National\nBank and chairman of the\nrecent new membership drive of\nthe Washington Chapter. American\nInstitute of Banking.\nSome idea of the success attained\nby Mr. Deyber and his\naids can be gathered from the\nfact that when the campaign\nwas launched, the local chapter\nboasted of only slightly more\nthan 300 members At the last\ncompilation, slightly more than\n800 members were totalled? j\nand returns are still straggling\nin. J\nCOTTON MARKET\nFEELS RELAPSE\nQuotations Suffer From\nHeavy Pressure and Rally\nFails.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 12. Heavy\npressure was applied to the cotton\nmarket today, and quotations suf- j\nfgred sharp losses. For a time there j\nwas some resistance against the j\nmovement downward, which came!\nmostly from new buyers taking ad- j\nvantage of the break to get some j\ncheap cotton.\nBut when this demand was exhaust\n?d the supply from sources\nthat had previously bought for a\nturn and from Southern interests.!\nproduced a very weak feeling from\nwhich the market showed little\nrally.\nInitial quotations were- 10 to 27,\npoints lower, with the trade fairly\nactive. The decline was due to sell-]\nIng by the South and Liverpool. The 1\nbreak extended to about 27 to 30 j\npoints below the close of Saturday j\nbefore it was checked by some* buy- j\ninp Wy the trade and covering by\nshorts. L?ater the market became:\nluiet. with traders waiting for the\ngovernment report.\nImmediately after the publication\nof the bearish government report\nthere was a Rood deal of unloading\nand short selling, causing severe de- j\ndines.\nThe Federal figures were followed\nby new low levels for the day. and\nlast prices were only a shade up j\nfrom the bottom. Final quotations\nshowed net losses of 67 to 87 points.\nSpot here was 75 points lower at j\n15.70 cents for middling; there were\nno sales. Spot at New Orleans was\nsteady witji middling unchanged at,\n14.75 cents; the sales were 1.77C;\nbales.\nThe market at New Orleans will\nnot be in session tomorrow, election j\nday.\nReceipts of cotton in bales at j\nsome of the leading points today,\nfollow: Qalveston. 16.350; New Or- j\nleans. 9.896: Savannah. 1.218; Nor-1\nfolk. 1.486; Augusta, 1.376; Houston,:\n18.271.\nA Christ\nThat Meanj\nToys are peris\nis soon speni\npass-book is a\nsion, an induct\ncosts the give\nwants to give\nand solves th\nfuture gifts\nWe have coil\nTHE WASHD\nAND TRUS1\nMai> Office,\nF Street at Niatfc\nf V\n\nY WANT ADS\nBUILDING\nSECTION TWO.\nOTCAGOWEffii\"\